An extreme struggle: MP3 readers against mobiles.
We'll advise you how to choose
While virtually all mobiles know how to read MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
It seems to be clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Notwithstanding that there are sufficient reasons for obtaining an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-quality expensive grammar to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the quality point of view, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
However, if there are vinyl discs in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you will probably dream of such a grammar.
It is the same as music during travels, i.e. compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one thing, it can be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, in the same way as a fan of Pink Floyd would have been hard to support listeners purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
There are two extremes, among which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The lifetime of batteries is also decisive
Some high-quality music readers are able to do much more than just play music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone calls and SMS, it is able to read music and movies, to record them, it has a variable quality camera and can, for example, be used for navigation.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into account, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Given that no refrigerator can grill meat and no television takes photographs, we are witnessing almost a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without disadvantages.
The greater the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two recharges will be.
And the reading of music is one of the most important energies.
It is rare for mobiles who are able to read music for 10 to 12 hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music readers (particularly the most rudimentary) are significantly more performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you may call from time to time, get, to be over, a second reload for work - this is even valid for more expensive devices.
There will be no problem for MP3 drives that are capable, following recharge, of a continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without a special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers can take it without reduction, given the small dimensions of the memory cards used in mobiles.
With regard to the readers, you do not need any software, except for the exception (iPod).
Just fill the music device from the computer through the USB connector.
Most mobiles and readers will create themselves a media library classified according to the name of the interpreter, the title of the album, style, or then according to the user's judgement.
Some devices display only one index with a tree structure, in the way of Windows Explore, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
In the choice of a concrete device, focus on the life of the accumulator, memory capacity, sound quality and type of output, and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and in the day you will only listen to it for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you will have enough any mobile reading MP3.
Practically all mobiles are able to do so today.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
Everyone can read the MP3 and the vast majority of music that will reach you will just have this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also read WMA format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-quality mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
Just visit the corresponding websites of the operator (or any other supplier) from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a convincing reason for obtaining a musical mobile.
Unfortunately, the supply of operators is poor and, in most cases, it is limited to fast-made radio tubes.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (either by GSM, Internet, or even by wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people still wear their motive on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have listeners or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use integrated drives, which have virtually all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 drives.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, we can already have a very suitable walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of regular listeners exit.
The price of the best phones and the best utilized, also equipped with a regular listener entry, does not exceed 15 thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
In fact, anyone can order the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command to that of a cassette post, commonly used in the past, or a grammophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by an enormous data transmission invoice.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you are not going to exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models in principle support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones even get out with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy another cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on capacity (max. 2 GB), you must not spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose specialised walkman mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the control ease is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went farther in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a lifetime of the accumulator (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) above, is provided by a MP3 player produced by one of the above brands.
A first virtual operator will win Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force classic operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already repeatedly mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are one of the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (the Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher in our homes than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some of the Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo.k, the President of the Czech Telecommunications Office Council (ČTÚ), who repeatedly stated that there was no room for another operator in Czech Republic, choiring with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network is apparently no longer having much chance (by the way, now he would hardly find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable price reduction, which then had to respond to by-products by conventional operators.
However, even before the party disorders such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile came into the market, voices similar to those heard today in our homes were allowed to be heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual Mobilking operator.
In only six months, this operator has succeeded in winning more than 100 thousand customers and has become the fifth operator in the country.
Let us add that behind Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which, among other things, has the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be effective, they need much less customers than a conventional operator.
They are exempt from the costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network, which are relatively high.
This is how virtual operators around the world profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in Britain at least twice the cost of its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, bet on an unusual target group can also be a good blow to advertising.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept could also work in our homes.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone's spokesman, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
More particularly, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, says mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project with success, but in Czech Republic negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said in a phone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesman of the financial group Penta.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were not in any case in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business client sector, has not, for a long time, concealed its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile services.
And the sooner it will be the best.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of us, we managed to make progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl's spokesman.
The future is therefore perhaps promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might be able to welcome the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for the moment, his creation is accompanied by complete silence.
"We do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to other very specific markets.
For the moment, no subjects with a complex and serious project in this area have contacted us," mentioned Vlastimil Srše.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Martina Kemrová's spokesman said in a rare agreement with the O2 statement, "We have not currently registered a viable and bilaterally beneficial project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate within such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone focuses on the fulfilment of requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the field of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe is the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to lower prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So what is the benefit of facilitating the arrival of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to be heard at the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to this.
The most apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, during the creation of the U:fon, was the pressure exercised by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidence of information available to the public from the ČTÚ web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon is ready to use as an argument to not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: "In addition, competition in the mobile market has recently been reinforced by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject it to high demands, especially its services."
However, given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power in Czech Republic to intervene in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, the latter adopted its typical position in the face of this problem.
"A virtual operator's entry into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached for the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not initially shown sufficient interest for conventional operators," explained in response to our question Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of ÚOHS.
A statement thus made would not be surprising by representatives of operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one benefits from its position on the market, such a statement is more than disgusting.
In particular, as Kristián Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be noted that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services."
However, pressure in the direction of a fair functioning of the market and price reduction is apparently not part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concordance of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, whether this really is a chance, arises naturally.
Similarly, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and hard competition.
"The Office has not found signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position and therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even the telecommunications regulator," explained Chaloupa's statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many discord points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitutes, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts are proposing a different view of things: in order to enable the creation of a virtual operator, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has logically the monopoly on his network.
This is why he must play a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting in a similar way.
However, complaints by many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Responding to the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, by which the ÚOHS washs its hands.
We have already met this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, we have not succeeded in moving into the innovation of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, an extension of the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this very well, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work
In other words, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo operator, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unseen.
These are companies publishing their own price list of mobile telephone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, there are companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile phone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these companies are generally only available to elected companies.
The magic tour consists of the fact that the company made before the operator belongs to a classic company client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she receives special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are referring to happened, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could lead to an interruption of collaboration with the society in question," answered our question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is fairly unlikely that a echo of such activity would not have been achieved to the managers of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, an operator does not pronounce itself against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring them unforgettable profits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
This is exactly what should seem strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another question arises to the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to content itself with the explanations of the operators, who claim that they have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant decrease in service prices.
However, in practically all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were sometimes more, sometimes less, trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in developed countries, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators, but those of their clients.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they finally obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the way of a hot potato that is dismantled by sending it to a close target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable for them in these cases.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the stab.
If the sliding information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at our home, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will hardly remain impassible to the rejection (discriminating) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the Best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national hymn.
Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national hymn Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The hymn was recorded again by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Ji★ Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Knřnková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremi★ and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the hymn.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national singing to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose to interpret solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"Since the beginning, I was trying to make sure that both singers, as well as the choir, had a good diction, so that the words were well understood, which they sang simultaneously," he explained.
The Czech national hymn will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
For the first time in 1834, the song Kde domov můj held on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), a Czech original piece of Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously adapted it.
After the creation of the Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national hymn.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
