If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of South Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This follows, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov prayed in the letter to the President of the United States not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and we want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that the American troops come into the German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, "Persons, to whom the fate of the Šumava holds the heart".
Given that the connection with Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, unreasonable attitude, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take into his hands the protectionorate of the Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign State, which oppresses and destroys minorities, and which in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter million inhabitants," says the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for vengeance of the Czech oppressors.
If the President of the United States doubted the views of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organise, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronate of the United States.
