The rats also have feelings
A rat or a cafard fleeing from the danger, does that mean he also feel fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have feelings.
But how can we verify that he feels the same thing when he is acting in the same way as we?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think to be true without having the evidence of it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without that I or anyone else have so far been able to prove it just as it is not possible to prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains will have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and deal with the issues of feeling or generally of consciousness, we enter hardly practical terrains because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is facing a danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he dies, flees or attacks.
Human beings are acting in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce from a comparable subjective life.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our lives subjective to that of animals difficult.
One of the aspects is that the circuits that are almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal side Cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the management and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other beings.
So at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal Cortex, including the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being even differs from the other primates.
Another significant particularity could be in the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence being linked to the language, this often means that his conscience depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness should not depend on the language, it would certainly influence it, so that the animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our state of consciousness.
That is why it is as difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internally and subjectively, does not allow itself to be measured or, due to this particular hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses great problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily scientifically accessible.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without taking into account their content, and that was exactly what happened in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, one focuses more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the weight of prefrontal Cortex in making visualization.
