No heels, no outer garments.
The essence of the great masters of the flamenco, freed from all tensions to get the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in privacy, in these moments unknown to the general public, where one discovers intimate gestures and stolen eyes of artists who don't care to get up on stage.
German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatrality of a few plays with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less famous side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes on the particular flamenco iconography from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flame Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of conveying on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists, you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and character.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of the flamenco stars.
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines", Bauer started a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a record camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the equipment, remind classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
This is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captures the public with his art.
The search for essentials and magic has been the constant of this work that is being presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about sixty photographed artists.
The project has turned into a flamenco anthology, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits presented to the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sports" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, knowing them and being able to enter their lives for a while or less.
I think in photography portrait is the most difficult genre.
You're in the face of people, characters you don't know sometimes or who leave you just a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas reality."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco titled "Flamenco - people" is presented at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at the 20th Street of Mata (rue parallel to the Hercules) which will be opened until 16 October next.
