The recidivists of the alcohol to the driver must install the 'alcolock' system.
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who had more than three administrative sanctions for alcoholicity to install a system in his vehicle that prevents the vehicle from being drunk, or if he does not breathe.
The initiative has already been announced last June and now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which it is considered a pilot project that will last one year.
Its purpose is to reintegrate the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State for Road Safety but also the Directorate-General for Routine Safety and the Institute of Technology for Auto Safety Foundation will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists who have been arrested for driving more than once in a drunken state, the car resumes.
The Alcolock would avoid this because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol rate in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before; or when the driver's alcohol rate is higher than the authorized.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is at the charge of the driver.
In this regard, a study in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65 per cent of the offences during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save life to 115 people every year.
This measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with these behaviours before they turn into criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be carried out by regular means, but, however, criminal reform requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have an experimental one.
Especially tomorrow, the Congress of Members will vote an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party that proposes to install this system in school buses as it has been done in France.
