Talking while sleeping
Some children talk during the night.
I do not refer to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk during their sleep.
The first time this happens, it may surprise you, but actually it doesn't matter.
It's a benign alteration of sleep called somnolocia.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking during the night.
This may occur very sporadically (e.g. in life associated with an episode of severe fever), or more periodically (all days, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child doesn't remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often associated with other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresies (sleeping in bed) or sleeping, but this is not always the case.
As we have already said, they can also be associated with very severe fever, stress or overexcitement.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a little quiet voice, with isolated words, murmurs or, on the contrary, with screams, crying, long speeches ...
In cases where sleeping becomes very common, it would be useful to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check whether there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We said that it is a benign impairment, that is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep impairment that can be treated (e.g., if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before sleeping.
Therefore, looking for quiet games and avoid television programs or series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have difficulty in relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm themselves inside.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleeps appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless for the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and so rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or to check out what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), don't have the temptation to question him to get information.
You won't get anything, because when you sleep, he's not conscious of being able to organize his thought.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you won't know what he's dreaming about, let's take care of how you interpret the information and the conclusions you're drawing from it.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even by joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
