Interview - Blood back safe
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he recognized the public's confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus in the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and the rage of the public, in February 1994, the Government of Canada initiated a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at highlighting the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and formulating recommendations that such a disaster should no longer occur.
While Judge Krever was late to submit his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee completed this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec started its activities, barely 38 per cent of people still trusted the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
With a strong effort to improve the safety of blood and work products on the ground over the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said, proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94 per cent of the Quebec population now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Decary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
As of its establishment, Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle on 28 September 1998.
At that time, many cases of the human form of the crazy cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were witnessed in Europe, explains the one that has been strong since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports, that when one does not know and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain which inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had been in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980 was therefore denied.
A few years ago, however, it was undoubtedly demonstrated that this disease was transmitted through blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle applied was meaningful."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique was found on the market: Nucleic Acid (TAN) tests that directly detect the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The TANs have allowed to shorten the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has significantly reduced the risk that some donors are infected without knowing and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year on the island of Réunion the Chikungunya virus, which, like the Western Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Decary, stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
"Demands increase because the population ages.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red or platelet recharge.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which is on average only 3 per cent of the Quebec people eligible for blood donation."
Any healthy person aged 18 years and older who meets the eligibility criteria can give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they are suffering from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is present, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to keep them and to encourage them to become regular donors.
As today's life is so terrified, one rarely finds the time to spend an hour giving her blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides blood products, but also human tissues, including bone transplantations, heart valves, eye gloves and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burned people.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The ombilical cord that was previously considered to be a biomedical waste contains blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our 1,000th sample of cord blood, and we expect it to take more than 1,000 a year.
We should start proposing it for transplants at the beginning of next year," explains Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"More mothers are disappointed to be unable to access it," because Héma-Québec has no means of proposing this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
