Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 30s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both Congress Chambers.
It includes: better control by the electorate of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for failure to pay, and a right to look at salaries paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
The US Secretary to the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, after a two-day bargaining marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush's representative, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and the ordinary Americans from the current crisis in Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do so, trauma, chaos and disruptions on the lives of the Americans will be enormous," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned to the sprint in the last few hours because of fear of the effect of a new failure on the mood of investors.
The time limit we had agreed was to open the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential election were rather favoured by the agreement, but without expressing their discontent that they were forced to reach this end.
Senator Barack Obama has committed itself to the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including those aimed at enabling owners to retain their home and on the salaries of the heads of the state-backed companies.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no reason to welcome.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the waves of American television.
Asked on another chain to know if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope yes."
"The great lines I've read [mount] that this is something that we all will have to digest and with which we will be able to progress.
The option of not doing anything is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the suspicious, risk-based and invenable claims from US financial institutions.
It occurs after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the break-up of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgages (subprimes) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and resulting in a liquidity freeze and the decay of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of republikan elects who had put the first draft agreement down last week.
It is believed that this impasse has emerged since the democrats have accepted that some "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government rather than purchased.
In order to round the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government was to assume losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of 250 billion, which can be added to 100 other billion if the President considers it necessary.
The further 350 billion payment should be supported by another vote of the Congress.
In exchange for his assistance, Washington will obtain participations in the rescued companies that will benefit him from dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to sell when the pain is passed.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for housing linked to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and departure allowances paid to the managers of the affected companies.
Architects of the plan would like to see it put to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Yesterday, there continued to be votes against this project, both in the Republican and the Democratic camp.
"Evidently, Washington does not hear you," said the Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, to his electors.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that involves benefiting taxpayers."
Animator of a small group in Congress called "the caucus of skeptics", the representative of the Democrat Brad Sherman presented things differently, but came to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred leading economic professors, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to us to say: Congress is asked not to press and carefully examine the way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis bank group for EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had renounced the acquisition of its competitor in full ruin since it lost €2 billion (2.9 billion) in the crisis of risk-based real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said yesterday the Dutch Minister of Finance, Wouter Bos.
In exchange, a right of vote is recovered in the bank and influence.
It is just something that savers and households now appreciate that time appears to be uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be nationalizing another bank that was misled by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, including over 41 billion US (75,5 billion) real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the British bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
