Next, on 8 October, the hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, having caused particularly serious damage, and other indictors have been arrested against them, for example, falsehood and use of falsehood.
According to the Public Prosecutor, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while benefits were justified by false invoices.
The government's and municipalities' money, approximately HUF 65 million in total, went to the Fiatal Baloldal movement's funds on the one hand and to some people's pockets on the other.
Their method, also made public by the investigation authorities, was to raise the money from subsidies obtained by issuing cost invoices, which did not provide any real benefit, and thus the associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, much of the bills were false.
For the latter, they purchased billbooks at the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies to be included on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
