The psychology of the auction: why do we spend more money?
In auction sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurology and economy at the University of New York have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in Science magazine, human beings do not want to be distanced in this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that's why they even prefer to pay too high prices.
These research attempted to develop a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auction sales.
One of the volunteer groups played the lottery, while the other group participated in auctioning ludics, while the researchers, using a functional magnetic resonance process (MRIf), analysed the active brain areas of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction, whose essential element is the third-party overauction, the group under the cerebral trunk, called striatum, moved intensively during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the "auto-stimulating" mechanism of the nervous system.
That is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak before the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economist members of this group of researchers continued financial monitoring analyses.
In these cases, three groups were confronted with a partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question and thus carried out their implementation.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were going to win the game, then they would receive an additional $15, in reward.
While the third group received these $15 before the auctions, the members of the group also lost that money in case they lost the auctions.
In fact, the difference between these two groups is that one focuses on victory, while the other focuses on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the players' team "contre failure" was willing to make higher bets than those made by the control group and the "for victory" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theories.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctioning only by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by developing, now, a third explanation." - noted Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When do we have to consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that 100 miles of patients who carry the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles are undergoing treatment, because they often do not know that they carry the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to liver-related infections caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Liver inflammation and yellowishness are characteristic, but pathogens and caused diseases differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the gastrointestinal tube (e.g.: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood viruses and organic fluids (sperma, vaginal secretion, saliva).
In any case, it is recommended for travellers to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, generally accompanied by general disorder, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then a visible yellowishness develops on the skin and on the white eye, the sheaths become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year, around the world, one million people die of the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know that the virus is affected, because the pathogenic gene destroys the liver cells in a subtle way. In many cases, the first symptoms occur only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
At present, there are 200 million chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a laboratory routine examination, it is advised to consult a doctor who treats as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, held for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representing patients around the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of the early diagnosis of the disease.
