Smart car imitates the bourdon's flight
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of an existing barrier detector already in nature?
Like, for example, the bee.
In the amazing project presented at the CEATEC, which took place in Japan, bourdoning bees gave the strategic idea of starting with Nissan's engineers, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacles detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-roboted system of BR23C, which he equipped with bee qualities, the final aim being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own oval space, which in reality resembles much our secured protection shell - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and public technological relations of the brand.
The face-to-face eye of the bee plays an important role, as it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the facet-to-face eye, engineers discussed the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the bow microprocessor, which transforms it into avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system at present, this avoidance manoeuvre is completely instinctive.
"If this was not the case, the mini auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Laboratoire Mobilité and the robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where collision is currently considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a glance.
Contrary to bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonal, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations of bees to avoid other bees, in our case, only the rotational movement, acceleration and slowdown as manoeuvres were used at the disposal of the mini auto robot
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and the energy concentrate is larger, making their lifetime longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is essential, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only deal with a few signals entering each second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with the intuitive logic based on the data of the previous manoeuvres. In this way, it only uses a few dozen kilo-octets of memory on a continuous basis.
We don't need a memory of giga-octet capacity, nor even giga-octets.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter the cars made in series in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
