Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports to the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, compared with one year earlier, decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry have only experienced a slight increase in the order of 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and shoes manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, and secondly, the production of shoes with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing of products and chemicals (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sector (1.4 per cent), in the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which account for a significant weight in national industrial production, prices have risen by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, prices in the oil processing sector were the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the manufacturing of metallurgical products, price increases were observed by 13.2%, while in the important field of food, beverages and tobacco, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent) as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and equipment (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases rose between 0.6 per cent and 9.1 per cent.
In the whole processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent of prices in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to sector allocations in August, it was the initiators of investment profit that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material production sectors for subsequent processing did not have any change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared with the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for subsequent processing (16.8 per cent).
In consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured by 6.8 per cent, while initiating profit sectors decreased by 1.4 per cent.
Export prices in the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while decreased by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment was weakened by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
