Mp3 pointed from the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to full volume music for a prolonged period using portable music devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a communication issued in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"from this scientific report-- let us read in the note-- it shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full volume music using portable music devices, for more than one hour per day and per week, are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who often use full volume portable music devices and mobile phones can unconsciously harm their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data, the responsible Ue continues - this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information publicly available.
In addition, we need to review existing control systems, given scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels requested the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise caused by them.
"The scientists-concludes the Ue- executive confirm that there are good reasons to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures might be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but concerns about hearing damage that may result from excessive exposure to such noise sources are increasing.
Such data may be clearly limited using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of noise exposure.
The Ue Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to full volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level at work.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This attracts 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to approximately 2.5 and 10 million people in the U.S.
Rome, Alemanno ordered the Commission to leave for the future of the capital.
Today we begin, in March we end, in June we will draw the sums.
