Students who are victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for one room.
The student rental market does not know a crisis
According to the latest Sunia survey, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to exclude the entire categories of young people, the right to study due to the very high overall costs that families of origin need to support- explains the head of Sunia's study office, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand of students has deformed the market so much that a generalized growth process has started for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also include a series of violations: free, non-registrated, unlimited rental contracts, sub-locations.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the review of tax are necessary to calm down prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza zone, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from a minimum of 650 euros (Band Nere Zone), to an average of 800 (Lambiate Zone, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria Zone)
In Florence, a bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room of about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in nearby areas of the University, they need 250/280 euros for a double bed, and from 370 to 500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros for one single, 450 for one bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euro for one single) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
Only if you get away from the peripheral areas: 300 euros for one bed, and 450 euros for one single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed you need 300/400 euros, for a simple one, you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas of Policlinico, Voero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 euros for one single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by extra community students, are recorded a subsequent abnormality: the rental rate for foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Goodbye old cinema Paradiso, the cities eliminate historical rooms.
Historical cinema rooms close in favour of Multiplex.
"A city without cinema rooms is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director in stage Giuseppe Tornatore illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the peripheral of large multi-salles, and the death of consumption of mono-rooms in the central areas of towns, is one of the major events that seems to us inevitable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
Disappearing, these are often historical and memorable places, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with which we shared a lot of path and so many emotions," observes the director of the Nuovo film Paradiso, a film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the Grand Prix of the sworn of Cannes, and who told the poetry of a provincial room, and nostalgia in a way to live the movie, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: over the past five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the rooms of the main cities that paid the most of them: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilie Romaine is in the lead with 82 single-room cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardia (41).
The evidence confirms that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the arrival of multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multisalle cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy over the past five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romania.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," says Anec's president Paolo Protti, "it is useful to build new structures, but it still needs to be guaranteed the survival of those already in existence, because when a farmroom in a city, they are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of credit deliberation for traders: the state's past debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, between €16 and €18 million per year is needed.
Let us note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of this kind in Italy, to defend and promote mono-room cinemas in historical and peripheral centres.
Among the proposed normative measures are tax facilitation measures for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators can enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and certain parking spaces.
"I like this initiative," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the Bologna example that introduces other measures.
However, it is obvious that, in contrast to the superpower of multiplex, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important for me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and teenagerhood, was the tincell that convinced me to make "New Paradiso cinema" which I have been thinking for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much shared emotions, I turn on the other side, not to see the black panels by dust.
